question: Is the following statement true or false? Fae is not small.
raw_logic_programs:
Predicates:
Wumpus(w) : wumpus
Brown(w) : wumpus is brown
Dumpus(d) : wumpus is a dumpus
Dull(d) : dumpus is dull
Yumpus(y) : dumpus is a yumpus
Metallic(y) : yumpus is metallic
Tumpus(t) : dumpus is a tumpus
Sour(t) : tumpus is sour
Numpus(n) : tumpus is a numpus
Opaque(n) : numpus is opaque
Impus(i) : numpus is an impus
Small(i) : impus is small
Jompus(j) : impus is a jompus
Zumpus(z) : zumpus is not small
Premises:
∀x (Wumpus(x) → Brown(x)) : Every wumpus is brown.
∀x (Wumpus(x) → Dumpus(x)) : Every wumpus is a dumpus.
∀x (Dumpus(x) → Dull(x)) : Every dumpus is dull.
∀x (Dumpus(x) → Yumpus(x)) : Every dumpus is a yumpus.
∀x (Yumpus(x) → Metallic(x)) : Yumpuses are metallic.
∀x (Yumpus(x) → Tumpus(x)) : Every yumpus is a tumpus.
∀x (Tumpus(x) → Sour(x)) : Tumpuses are sour.
∀x (Tumpus(x) → Numpus(x)) : Tumpuses are numpuses.
∀x (Numpus(x) → Opaque(x)) : Every numpus is opaque.
∀x (Numpus(x) → Impus(x)) : Each numpus is an impus.
∀x (Impus(x) → Small(x)) : Each impus is small.
∀x (Impus(x) → Jompus(x)) : Every impus is a jompus.
∀x (Zumpus(x) → Not(Small(x))) : Each zumpus is not small.
Wumpus(fae) : Fae is a dumpus.
Conclusion:
¬Small(fae) : Fae is not small.
